details.name: Royal London University Hospital
details.description:
The Royal London Hospital is home to one of the largest children’s hospitals in the UK with one of London's busiest paediatric accident and emergency departments.

It is also home to London’s Air Ambulance service and one of the capital's leading trauma and emergency care centres and hyper-acute stroke centres.

The Breathe London Node is located near the entrance to A&E to assess the exposure of visitors, patients and staff at the hospital.

details.name: North Middlesex University Hospital
details.description:
North Middlesex University Hospital has been serving the community for over a century. The first hospital buildings on the present site were built in 1909.

The hospital has expanded and modernised over the years, improving the medical, surgical, stroke and children’s services including a brand new maternity and neonatal unit. The new maternity unit is equipped with with state-of-the-art facilities and is among the best NHS maternity units in the country.

The Breathe London Node is located by the front entrance and serves to assess the exposure of visitors, patients and staff at the hospital.

details.name: Newham University Hospital
details.description:
Newham University Hospital serves one of the most diverse populations in England. The hospital cares for more than 500 patients in its A&E department every day and is home to one of the largest maternity units in the UK with more than 6,000 births each year.

The hospital's state-of-the-art Rainbow Centre is geared up to meet the needs of its young patients and their families in a child-friendly environment. 

The Breathe London Node is located on a flag pole by the entrance to the A&E department where patients are picked up and dropped off.

details.name: Whipps Cross Hospital
details.description:
Whipps Cross Hospital has a strong reputation as a centre of excellence for various specialist services, including urology, ENT, audiology, cardiology, colorectal surgery, cancer care and acute stroke care.

Thanks to £6.7m in funding from Barts Charity, the hospital is making a series of improvements to its Maternity and Neonatal services to improve the environment and prepare for an increase in birth rates in its local population. This will include a dedicated clinical research hub for women's services.

The Breathe London Node is located by the main entrance near the car park to assess exposure for staff, patients and visitors.

details.name: Charing Cross Hospital
details.description:
Charing Cross Hospital provides a range of acute and specialist services, a 24/7 accident and emergency department and hosts the hyper acute stroke unit for the region.

It is also a growing hub for integrated care in partnership with local GPs and community providers.

The Breathe London Node is located on a wall near the entrance on Fulham Palace Road.

details.name: Royal Free Hospital
details.description:
Established in 1828 by William Marsden, the Royal Free's founding principle was that they would take in anyone who needed treatment – the first hospital in London to do so and the only London hospital to stay open during the 19th-century cholera epidemics.

In the 21st century, the hospital continues to lead improvements in healthcare and is proud to have some of the best clinical outcomes in the country.

The Breathe London Node is located in the busy pick-up and drop-off area by the entrance assessing exposure of staff, visitors and patients.

details.name: Great Ormond Street Hospital
details.description:
Great Ormond Street Hospital is an international centre of excellence in child healthcare. It's mission is to put the ‘child first and always’.

Since its formation in 1852, the hospital has been dedicated to children’s healthcare and to finding new and better ways to treat childhood illnesses.

The Breathe London Node is located by the main entrance which receives 237,908 outpatient visits and 43,218 inpatient visits every year.

details.name: St Thomas' Hospital
details.description:
Guy's and St Thomas' is one of the busiest and most successful NHS foundation trusts in the country.

The hospital provides a full range of hospital and community services for people in Lambeth, Southwark and Lewisham, as well as specialist care for patients from further afield including cancer, renal, orthopaedic and cardiovascular services.

The Breathe London Node is located on a pole by the main entrance off Westminster Bridge.

Since no other closeby location could be found for the reference monitoring, it was moved just round the corner to Laurence House, and this Breathe London Node installed on the wall opposite the original inlet.  This will help continue the valuable long term data set from this location.

details.name: Melcombe Primary School
details.description: Melcombe Primary School is a two-form entry school located within the London Borough of Hammersmith & Fulham. The school was awarded a Healthy Schools silver award in 2019 by the National Healthy Schools Programme.

details.name: William Hogarth School
details.description: The William Hogarth School is located just north of the A4 in Chiswick in the London Borough of Hounslow. Sitting at the heart of the local community, the school’s atmosphere and ethos reflect the rich cultural diversity that surrounds it.

details.name: Ark Byron Primary Academy
details.description: Ark Byron Primary Academy is located on the edge of Acton Park in the London Borough of Ealing. The Academy has six year groups, ranging from Reception to Year 5 and a total of 360 pupils. Their motto “Courage to reach for the sky” reflects the high aspirations they have for each pupil, encouraging them to aim high in everything that they do.

details.name: Christopher Hatton Primary School
details.description: Christopher Hatton is a happy, ambitious and inclusive school reflecting the rich diversity of families in its area. Its curriculum emphasises the environment and the Rights of the Child,

details.name: St Annes RC Primary School
details.description: St Anne's R.C. lies at the centre of a vibrant local community in Vauxhall, south London. Around thirty languages are represented by it's 400 pupils. The school has close links to local parishes and communities and the teachings of the Catholic Church underpin everything the school does.

details.name: Charlotte Sharman Primary School
details.description: Charlotte Sharman is located in the diverse community of Elephant and Castle. All pupils are now undertaking a whole school topic 'We can save the world', learning about how children can make the world a better place.

details.name: Oaklands Secondary School
details.description: Oaklands Secondary School is a comprehensive community school of 909 11 – 18 learners. Located in Bethnal Green, the school is committed to serving the local community and being active citizens in the wider international community.

details.name: Bonner Primary School
details.description: Bonner Primary School Bethnal Green is a two form entry school taking children from Reception until Year 6. The school has achieved UNICEF's Gold Award as a Rights Respecting School.

details.name: Tower Bridge Primary School
details.description:
Tower Bridge Primary School is one of three Bridges Federation Schools. It is located next to the iconic Tower Bridge, near the Thames and the Tower of London. 
The school is part of a diverse community in which a wide range of faiths, languages and cultures are represented.

details.name: St Annes C of E Primary School
details.description: St Anne’s is a one-form entry school in the heart of a diverse and vibrant Wandsworth community. Activities include, collaboration with neighbouring schools, exploring and understanding how to care for their environment, supporting local elderly people within the community, communicating and sharing experiences with their link school in New Delhi, India and taking part in an annual United Nations General Assembly, where pupils debate global issues with other schools.

details.name: Alice Model Nursery School
details.description:
Alice Model Nursery School is a small, warm and welcoming school in the heart of London’s East End.
Providing a safe, exciting and inclusive learning environment for children full of stimulating, inspiring learning opportunities.
Alice Model MBE was an East End social reformer who inspired the development of the Nursery. Developed from the Jewish day nursery she founded in 1901, it was for children of all religions, an ethos which continues to this day.

details.name: Marner Primary School
details.description: Marner Primary School is a large three form entry school within a diverse community located in Tower Hamlets in the East End of London. The school is a recent recipent of funding from the Mayor’s Community Green Space fund. This funding enables the school to transform its playground with a range of green measures to reduce pollution exposure from the highly polluted A12 and nearby Devas Street.

details.name: Rachel Keeling Nursery
details.description: Rachel Keeling Nursery School is a state maintained school in Bethnal Green, Tower Hamlets, providing nursery places for 3 & 4 year olds. The school was named in honour of one of the suffragettes; Rachel Susanna Keeling. Driven by quality with a highly dedicated multi disciplinary staff, children at the nursery engage in a wide range of learning experiences.

details.name: Meath Gardens Children's Centre
details.description:
This is one of nine Nodes deployed at locations which are expected to have low pollution levels, but which are representative of large areas around them.  This provides balance across the network with many other Nodes being at higher pollution locations.

With the help of Tower Hamlets local authority, this node has been installed on Smart Street, near Meath Gardens Children and Family Centre. Meath Gardens Children and Family Centre is used by many parents and children in the community. It hosts health clinics as well as, baby and toddler groups.  The node will also be representing those living nearby and those using Meath Gardens Park.

details.name: Tavistock Road, Hillingdon
details.description: This Node was located on Tavistock Road because the local community had raised concerns over the impact of traffic associated with nearby industrial uses.

details.name: Stockwell Primary
details.description:
Stockwell Primary School is located in Lambeth for children aged two to eleven years old. With an experienced and passionate team of staff, committed to providing each and every child with an exceptional start to their education by creating a unique and interesting learning environment, full of opportunities within and beyond the classroom.
This node is sponsored by the Mayor of London to measure the air pollution the children and staff experience while at school.

details.name: East Sheen Primary School
details.description:
East Sheen Primary is a community school on the Upper Richmond Road in The London Borough of Richmond upon Thames. It's a three form entry primary school with an excellent reputation for providing fun and happiness, combined with high standards of education. As a school, they are committed to providing an outdoor environment for children that will provide stimulating and challenging learning. Such an environment supports both the curriculum and the extended school day programme.
This node is sponsored by the Mayor of London to measure the air pollution the children and staff experience while at school.

details.name: St James Hatcham C of E School
details.description: St. James Hatcham CE Primary School is an inclusive and aspirational community, committed to ensuring that every single child develops to the best of their ability and excels in all areas. The school is located just south of New Cross Gate Station, close to the A2.

details.name: Oxford Gardens Primary School
details.description:
Oxford Gardens Primary School is a unique learning community in the heart of North Kensington. The school strives to develop a rich and varied curriculum to enable learners to achieve their aspirations. The school's Vision is that every pupil will strive to be the very best that they can be. Creativity and Innovation, underpinned by high standards and expectations for all are at the heart of all of the school's activities.
This node is sponsored by the Mayor of London to measure the air pollution the children and staff experience while at school.

details.name: Gospel Oak Primary School
details.description: Gospel Oak Primary School is committed to being an inclusive, community school. Through a broad and relevant curriculum the school aims to provide every child with the opportunity to develop their own interests and meet new challenges.

details.name: St Mary Magdalene CE School
details.description: St. Mary Magdalene CE School Peninsula site is the first all- through school in Royal Greenwich. The school is committed to developing both academic and personal excellence, applauding achievement, cherishing success and celebrating diversity.

details.name: Scotts Primary School
details.description: Scotts Primary is a community school catrering for children between the ages of 4 to 11 years of age. The school is fortunate to have large open spaces around the school, where children are free to play.  These include quiet spaces, where shaded seating is available. Scotts is placed at the very top of the 2017-18 Havering Primary School League tables for pupil progress and attainment and has achieved 16th place out of all the schools in England.

details.name: The Orion Primary School
details.description:
The Orion Primary School, which opened in 2000, aims to provide a primary school education with a difference. The school inspires children to be kind, caring individuals with high aspirations and very high standards in the essential academic areas of reading, writing and maths.
This node is sponsored by the Mayor of London to measure the air pollution the children and staff experience while at school. It is located in the children’s playground near doors and windows leading to the classrooms.

details.name: Wessex Gardens Primary School
details.description: Wessex Gardens Primary School in Brent aims to grow kind, confident, resilient and independent lifelong learners in a trusting and honest environment. Pupils are motivated and supported to reach their full potential as they continue to aspire to excellence.

details.name: Oakdale Junior School
details.description: Oakdale Junior School is a community school in the London Borough of Redbridge. The school admits children between the ages of seven and eleven.

details.name: St John's Upper Holloway CE Primary School
details.description: St John's Upper Holloway C.E. Primary School is a one form entry primary school, catering for children from 3 to 11 years old. As a church school, it serves the diverse local community and prides itself on its supportive, inclusive ethos.

details.name: Lordship Lane Primary School
details.description: Lordship Lane Primary School is a large primary school based in busy Wood Green. The school aims to give every child the best start to their education. The school's six core values are: Success, Perseverance, Ambition, Respect, Creativity and Independence.

details.name: William Patten Primary School
details.description: William Patten Primary School in Stoke Newington has high expectations of all children and staff and high standards of teaching and learning. It provides a friendly, supportive and purposeful school community which values all its members.

details.name: Haimo Primary School
details.description: Haimo Primary School in Eltham is a special place which promotes care and respect for each other at all times and is fully supported and valued by the community. The school provides a safe and friendly environment in which to provide the best possible learning experience for its children. The school also offers a wide variety of extra curricular activities and the children are encouraged to participate.

details.name: Guy's Hospital
details.description: Guy's Hospital was established in 1721 by philanthropist Thomas Guy. In 1974, the hospital added the 34-storey Guy's Tower and 29-storey Guy's House which is dedicated to improving outcomes of conditions such as Alzheimer's disease, stroke, Parkinson's disease and spinal cord injury. A new cancer centre was completed in April 2016. The hospital is part of King's Health Partners an academic health sciences centre, which is pioneering health research providing high quality teaching and education.

details.description: St Clement Danes has existed for more than 300 years and is steeped in history. The school makes use of it's magical West End setting and children perform on the stage of the Royal Opera House annually and regularly visit a wide range of local galleries, parks and museums which include Somerset House, The Globe Theatre, The London Transport Museum, The National Gallery, the Tate and the British Museum.

With tourist attractions, businesses and the University of Westmnster  close by there is significant foot fall at this crossing point/exiting the station and is a specific area of interest for the GLA.

The immdiate area has a number of retail and food outlets and is a specific area of interest for the GLA.

details.name: Hogarth Roundabout - Great West Road Chiswick
details.description: This Node is located alongside the A4  at Hogarth Roundabout.  It is located on the south side outside residential properties and a pub , and is at a pedestrian crossing point for the roads.   This part of the A4  is a specific area of interest for the GLA

details.name: Martin Primary School-Playground
details.description: This Node is located within the front playground at Martin Primary School, East Finchley, N2 9JP close to the A1000/High Road. The A1000/High Road is a well-known source of air pollution due to traffic, and runs along the western boundary of the playground. This monitor will provide information on the potential level of exposure to air pollution for those using the playground (children, parents, and school staff), as well as the potential air quality impacts of the new A1000 cycle lane.

details.name: Peareswood Primary School - Bexley
details.description: This Node has been installed in Bexley’s “Focus Area” immediately outside a local Primary School.  The sensor lies 56m to the East of the A206.  The location is intended to be analogous to air pollution concentrations in the primary school playground.

details.name: Chrisp Street Market - Tower Hamlets
details.description: Chrisp street has been chosen as location for one of the Breathe London Network nodes, because Chrisp market is one of the key areas of the Tower Hamlets Business Low Emissions Neighbourhood (BLEN). The BLEN aims to address environmental and air quality issues, which is of the utmost importance for BID businesses. Around the Chrisp market area, an electric cargo bike will be implemented for businesses.

details.name: Redbridge Ley Street BLEN
details.description:
This Node is located within Redbridge's Business Low Emission Neighbourhood on Ley Street opposite the transport depot and is just north of Seven King's Primary School.

Originally located on the west side of LeyStreet , about 60m north of this location, it was moved to the east side to give a better location for the solar panel operation.

details.name: Middlesex Street Estate
details.description:
This Node is in the middle of the Middlesex Street Estate, a Corporation of London housing estate comprising approximately 280 residential flats. 
Residents are of all ages, from newborns to centenarians and some have lived on the estate for around 40 years. The flats are built around and overlook a Podium; windows facing the podium are opened to provide ventilation to the flats. Within a short walk, the Estate is surrounded by major roads including Bishopsgate, Hounditch, Commercial Street and Aldgate High Street.
Residents said that they are very interested to monitor the air quality 'as they are breathing the local air 24/7. This is in contrast to City workers who typically are in the area up to 8 hours a day and up to five days a week and many of them spend most of that time in air conditioned offices.’

details.name: Bedford Hill - Wandsworth

This is the first of many Breathe London Nodes to be installed in the borough to try and give everyone an idea of levels of pollutant in real time.

details.name: Silvertown Tunnel access corridor  - Silvertown Way
details.description:
This Node has been placed close to a masterplan redevelopment area with high density residential development near to completion on each side of the access road (Silvertown Way).  
A residential street canyon is forming on the northern approach road to the Silvertown Tunnel (which is currently under construction, due for completion in 2023). Once the tunnel is open, the traffic volume and the risk of exposure to poor air quality for new residents will increase. The monitor could report on pre and post construction air quality concentrations to feed into the decision making for any mitigation requirements.

details.name: Horn Link Way j/w Peartree Way
details.description:
This node is solar powered and mounted on a lamppost in a roadside location.  The node is positioned here to review levels of pollution arising from both road traffic and fugitive emissions from industry.
The location is adjacent to part of the Greenwich Millennium Village, a strategic regeneration site within the Royal Borough of Greenwich. It received planning permission circa 2012 to deliver new residential units along with commercial, retail and community uses. The scheme has been built out in phases and has delivered a significant number of residential units that have made an important contribution to the annual housing targets within the Borough. The residential developments are bordered by long standing industry including, aggregate and cement works, and waste transfer operations. These industries supply an array of materials to support the construction sector and infrastructure projects in both Greenwich and the wider city.

details.name: Ceres Road, j/w Bannockburn Road - Bannockburn Primary School
details.description:
This node is solar powered and mounted on a lamppost to capture levels of pollution from road traffic in the vicinity. 
Bannockburn Primary School is a diverse learning community located in Plumstead that provides the best possible support in enabling pupils to achieve their best. The school is spread across two sites both located within the Plumstead area. Pupils from Reception to Year 2 are based at the High Street site which is closest to where the node is located. The school has high aspirations for pupils, their families and the community of Plumstead. The Schools Vision is 'Growing Together, Learning for Life'.
The area surrounding the school site has been identified as having a high proportion of private rented housing, and in particular Houses in multiple occupation (HMO). With a localised Nepalese speaking community, the Council's Environmental and Housing Services are working closely with charity and community groups to better engage with this community on Environmental and Housing matters.

details.name: Beresford Square, Woolwich, London SE18 6AY
details.description:
This node is solar powered and mounted on a lamppost in the town centre.  The node is positioned here to capture levels of pollution in this public open space. Sources of pollution include road traffic and construction works in the vicinity. 

Beresford Square is a pedestrianised town and market square in Woolwich in the Royal Borough of Greenwich. The square is home to a council-run market, dating back to the 1600s, selling general goods, providing bike repairs and food vendors with outdoor seating. The market operates six days per week and includes the location of the main gate of the old Royal Arsenal. The surrounding area includes the Woolwich Arsenal DLR Station, Beresford Street (A206), and the Woolwich redevelopment site at Royal Arsenal; a waterside housing and retail development area adjacent to the new Crossrail station.

details.name: Royal Hill, London, SE10 8RZ, adjacent to James Wolfe Primary School
details.description: This node is solar powered and mounted on a lamppost at a roadside location adjacent James Wolfe Primary School. Local communities include both residents and students. The surrounding area forms part of the West Greenwich Low Traffic Neighbourhood and local resident groups have asked about the impact of this scheme on local air quality.

details.name: John Wilson Street, Woolwich, adjacent to St Mary Magdalene C of E School
details.description: This node is solar powered and mounted on a lamppost at a roadside location adjacent to the A205 pedestrian subway and St Mary Magdalene C of E School on John Wilson Street (A205 South Circular). Local communities include residents and students. The surrounding area includes Ferry view Health Centre and the Woolwich Ferry Terminal. The node location marks the edge of the London Ultra Low Emission Zone (ULEZ) extension up to the South Circular which comes into effect on 25th October 2021.

details.name: Amhurst Road, Hackney
details.description:
The site is a kerbside location adjacent to a moderately busy road right in the centre of the borough of Hackney.
At this point, Amhurst Road is predominantly residential. The properties consist of a mix of residential blocks as well as some larger, older houses, many of which have been converted into separate residential units. Therefore, there will be a relatively high number of people in the area who may be affected by air pollution.
Among these are the residents of the Downs Estate. The estate includes 210 homes and is managed by a Tenant Management Organisation. The TMO has been instrumental in delivering improvements to the homes and this has included planting and landscaping works. Locating a Breathe London Node on their doorstep provides an opportunity to help further the interests of residents in their local environment and to see changes in air pollution over time. This we hope can encourage behaviour change and also help to raise awareness of their successes.

details.name: Whitehall Park School
details.description: In 2018 Islington started monitoring air quality outside every school in the borough using diffusion tubes, which provide monthly readings of the pollutant NO2. The tube for Whitehall Park School was located on Hornsey Lane and measured some of the highest pollution levels for schools in the borough, in contrast to modelled data for the school, and we think the Node will be a good way to help investigate further.

details.name: St Stephen's CE Primary School
details.description:
Air pollution is a serious issue, which  affects all of us, whether foetus, child, adult and elderly.
In the autumn 2021 a group of locals got together and created a community group 'Clean Air Bayswater’  to find a way to reduce the air pollution levels in our area.
We applied for and were very pleased  to be granted a Breathe London air pollution monitor, which will enable us to track and address air pollution in our local area.
We have developed a 12 month local community campaign to raise awareness among residents, businesses, schools and GPs of air pollution and how it impacts our health, irrespective of our age. This will involve a school education programme,  community events for residents and local business engagement activities.
Our aim is to improve the air we breathe by asking everyone living or working in Bayswater to join in, and take some simple steps to reduce air pollution in our area.  We are looking to work with other clean air groups to collaborate and share learning, so that we can all make as big a difference as possible.
We will also be looking for Westminster City Council to take action to support our campaign and actively reduce key issues such as idling.  
We believe that together we can make a difference.   Air pollution affects our lungs, heart and brains. We need to take action now. There is no excuse - The Clean Air Bayswater Group

details.name: Shelbourne Road
details.description:
Healthy Streets North Tottenham are a group of local residents striving for better, less polluted streets. We came together in 2020 to tackle the dominance that through-traffic has on our neighbourhood.

The rise in traffic has had a disproportionate effect on North Tottenham and the people who live here. Every day, residents experience 5000 vehicles passing their homes, which severely impacts our health, safety, lifestyle, social connections and ability to build a strong community. 

By harnessing the air quality data captured by this node, we hope to be able to persuade decision-makers at Haringey Council to take action on the ill effects of traffic pollution and implement changes which work for and benefit local residents. It will also help to raise awareness within the community and encourage others to tackle air pollution in North Tottenham.

details.name: Victoria Park Harriers
details.description:
Victoria Park Harriers and Tower Hamlets Athletics Club is based at St. Augustine’s Hall in the north-east corner of Victoria Park in Tower Hamlets, London. It was formed in 2001 as a merger of Victoria Park Harriers (founded in 1926) and Tower Hamlets Athletics Club (founded in 1976). The club is open to all regardless of ability from the age of 9 upwards and coached training sessions occur at St. Augustine’s Hall, Mile End Stadium and the London Marathon Community Track at least twice a week. The active membership of approximately 450 athletes includes track, field, road and cross-country athletes, from beginners to Olympians. The club reflects the diversity of East London and has close links to local schools through our junior athletes.

While Mile End Stadium and the London Marathon Community Track are both over 50 metres away from busy roads and thus classified as urban background locations, St. Augustine’s Hall is about 20 metres from the A106, close to the junction with the A12, which results in poor air quality, as reported by the Breathe GB campaign, which found that St. Augustine’s Hall had the worst air quality of any sports facility in England with an average of 67 µg/m3 of NO2 and 17 µg/m3 of PM2.5 in 2018.

The Club is looking forward to using the data from the Breathe London node, which will improve the ability of Club members and local residents to avoid high pollution episodes and provide them with the data necessary to advocate for measures to improve local air quality.

details.name: Elmhurst Gardens
details.description: This monitor was secured by Woodford Green resident Lydia Fraser-Ward to measure the levels of air pollutants in Elmhurst Gardens, E18. After spending two years visiting the park every day with her toddler, she became increasingly concerned about the air quality in the children’s playground and the effect it could be having on her son’s health. This area of the park backs onto the North Circular / A406 where it meets a major interchange with the M11 at the Charlie Brown’s Roundabout. After weeks of research she found that there were no air monitors provided by the local authority in the nearby vicinity, and that there was very limited data recorded specifically in parks and play areas relating to air pollution. Lydia joined clean air campaign group Mums for Lungs and reached out to a number of community groups, schools, environmental projects and parents in the local area to raise awareness about this issue. With their support she put together a short film to apply to the Breathe London Community Programme for this air quality node. The data will be used to inform whether further mitigation measures are needed to protect park and playground users from the motorway’s toxic air.

This location has been chosen as it is adjacent to one of the two entrance roads to the Denmark Hill hospital site.  
Data from an ANPR camera records at least 60,000 vehicles a month enter the hospital site by this road.  
Located nearby is the main entrance to the Golden Jubilee Hospital Wing which is also the main drop off area for patient transport vehicles.    
The monitor is also next to the hospital pavement used by staff and visitors and a pedestrian crossing.   
It is hoped that a monitor in this location will record the impact of the vehicle activity on the air quality of staff and patients that visit or work on the Denmark Hill site and lead to initiatives that bring about an improvement in air quality.

It is also a stretch of road used by local parents and children heading to school and the nearby swimming pool. Shadwell Responds and the local community have plans to develop a piazza to calm traffic and provide a safer and greener crossing area for pedestrians. The Node will help make the case for public realm improvements here.

details.description:
We want to use data from our Breathe London Node as a starter for improvements in air quality for those using and working in the Brunswick shopping centre, as well as those of us who live here.
Most of Camden has illegal air quality. Only Russell Square is - sometimes - legal.
The Brunswick Centre is between Russell Square (to the south-west) and Brunswick Square Gardens / Coram Fields (to the east). 
If we're WHO compliant, maybe that implies that the trees and green spaces nearby need to be even more positively promoted in other parts of Camden and London?
If we’re not compliant, is the issue commercial NOx or PM2.5 - from the shopping centre running through the Centre? 
Or is it the residential heating? That’s not included by Camden Council in its targets, even though we’ve got huge un-insulated windows (which are specifically included in the special architectural ‘listing’ of the Centre).
See more details on our community breathe london website: https://community.breathelondon.org/c/brunswick-tenants-and-residents-association/

details.name: Ray Lodge Primary School - Redbridge Mums for Lungs
details.description:
Ray Lodge Primary School is set in the heart of Woodford Green next to Ray Park. Although it enjoys the wildlife, biodiversity and picturesque setting that this green space provides, it is also situated on a busy road which runs under the M11 situated close by. Mums for Lungs Redbridge - a grassroots organisation made up of local residents all connected by a shared concern about air quality - was keen to work with the school to monitor levels of localised pollution coming from traffic on nearby roads and how this may be affecting the outdoor play areas of the school. 
 
Our group actively campaigns throughout the London Borough of Redbridge for more air quality monitoring in outdoor play areas and gyms, whilst also supporting parents to set up School Streets and raises awareness of the risks of idling car engines and wood burning. This monitor was secured by Woodford Green resident Rachel Southern in partnership with Mums for Lungs Redbridge Coordinator Lydia Fraser-Ward. Lydia was fortunate enough to receive an air monitor in Round 1 of the Breathe London Community Programme for the children’s outdoor playground in Elmhurst Gardens, South Woodford, which is located next to the North Circular.
 
The data from this Breathe London node will be used to inform the school and local residents of levels of nitrogen dioxide and particulate matter in the area. This information will be highly valuable and will inform whether further mitigation measures are needed to reduce air pollution levels around the school, whilst raising awareness more generally with parents about air quality in the neighbourhood.

details.name: Residents Action on Climate and Health
details.description:
About the group

REACH (Residents Environmental Action on Climate and Health) is a sub group of the Hampstead Garden Suburb (HGS) Residents association with a number of key stated aims including ;
•        To support Suburb residents in preparation for environmental challenges by taking initiatives that will play a part in reducing our contribution to emissions and thus to the warming of the planet 
•        Consider actions we can take to reduce local pollution and enhance biodiversity.
•        Consult and co-operate with LB Barnet, HGS Trust, City of London, Transport for London, Environment Agency, and other relevant bodies as applicable.
•        Aim is to achieve Net Zero greenhouse gas emissions from the area by 2040 and to work with residents and relevant stakeholders to achieve this ambitious target.
Node location 

One key area of concern that REACH has identified within HGS is air quality (AQ) as the Suburb is bordered and dissected by some of London’s busiest roads, including the A40, the A1, East End Road and the Finchley Road. The lack of meaningful AQ data within the suburb means we can’t take steps to identify and address the root cause (whether it is vehicles, buildings, or wood burners), educate residents and inform change in HGS and the wider area. There is, perhaps, a preconception that there is no AQ problem in the suburb because it is indeed founded on the Garden City principles of open green spaces. However. Whilst there is an obvious impact on residents and businesses that border these roads it also creates and number of “rat runs”  Meadway is one of these roads, it is also part of the H2 bus route .

details.name: Belvedere Road
details.description:
Like other areas of London, we know that the South Bank and people who live, work and visit here are adversely affected by ambient air pollution, with concentrations of nitrogen dioxide a particular concern. However, real-time air pollution monitoring in the South Bank has previously been limited to St Thomas’ Hospital. We have therefore commissioned a high-density mini network of eight measurement nodes to give a picture of current pollution levels across a range of locations that reflect the different urban environments found across the South Bank. This will give us great baseline data to help inform future environmental improvement projects.

Belvedere Road is a quiet road but it is regularly used by coaches and tour buses, which have bus stands along it. It is used by a mixture of residents, employees and tourists, with people frequently spending periods of time within Jubilee Gardens which are adjacent to the Belvedere Road node. Thank you to Lambeth Council for hosting the node on their land.

The South Bank Business Improvement District (BID) was set up in 2014 to improve the management of South Bank in the face of increasing footfall and falling public spending. We fund and support several public realm services, including enhanced security, cleaning and litter picking, and help to promote South Bank as a leading visitor destination and as the cultural heart of London. We are a voice for South Bank businesses and provide a wealth of networking opportunities to the organisations in our BID area through event and networking programmes.

The work of South Bank BID is achieved by working in collaboration with others who share our vision for the future prosperity of the South Bank, including South Bank Employers’ Group, South Bank and Waterloo Partnership, the Visitor Management Group, South Bank Marketing and Venues Groups and South Bank Business Watch. South Bank BID is an independent organisation, governed by a Board of Directors drawn from a range of businesses within the BID area and who work to support all our levy paying members and to represent their views.

details.description:
Air on the Green would like to better understand the significance of charcoal burning and other unfiltered particulate emissions from restaurants on air quality and health. The concern is that high levels of particulates in unfiltered restaurant pollution might be putting residents at risk of a range of health impacts, including respiratory and cardiovascular risks. 
 
Legislation passed in 2021 now makes it illegal to emit visible smoke from a chimney. However currently the local council does not act on complaints.
The installation of an air monitoring node in an enclave of student housing, flats and houses protected from road pollution but vulnerable to pollution from charcoal burning in restaurants to both north and south (depending on the direction of the wind) is an interesting opportunity to assess the impact of restaurants on local air quality. 
The node will enable us to gather and disseminate crucial data, which we hope will raise awareness of any effect on public health of charcoal burning, and of the potential to improve air quality by means of filtration. 
If the impact of charcoal burning in restaurants is found to be a significant concern, we hope to use this data to set a precedent for communities across the country affected by the same issue so that we can more effectively campaign to our councils. It is also our hope that a case can be made for a scrappage scheme for extraction ducts that could result in a significant improvement in urban air quality. Such a scrappage scheme would help defuse the tensions that inevitably arise when one group asks another group to spend money on improvements.

details.name: NW7hub
details.description: This node is positioned where the A1 and A41 trunk roads are conjoined, a site of very slow moving heavy traffic during rush hour periods. It is also in Mill Hill Broadway which, with its shops, restaurants and bus stops, is a place of heavy pedestrian footfall.

details.name: Willesden High Street
details.description: Willesden High Street (A407), one of the longest on London, is an important arterial road that connects Willesden Green to the North Circular Road and runs parallel to the railway tracks from Willesden Green underground station to Dollis Hill and beyond. The high street which also stretches to Duddenhill Lane is dotted with light indistrial businesses. Willesden Bus Garage and construction of new residential developments, all of which add to and trap pollution at street level. Pedestrians, local business, residents and school children all share these busy streets with buses, cars, motorbikes and heavy good vehicles, breathing in the small particulates and other emissions. The Breathe London node is an important tool in helping us to tackle what we believe is the serious but often forgotten threat of air pollution.

details.name: Upminster Road North
details.description: This Node is part of a small network being deployed within Rainham in order to investigate issues with recurring fires at a nearby historical  landfill.  The data from this Node will illustrate the levels of pollution the local residents are exposed to, and will ,along with long term existing monitoring close by, be fed into additional analysis being commissioned by London Borough of Havering.

details.name: Whitfield Nursery Playground
details.description: Fitzrovia Trust is a registered charity. Our air pollution monitor is based in a local nursery playground.  We want to understand the current levels of air pollution in Fitzrovia and work with local clinicians and scientists to help objectively examine the impact this is having on users of the nursery, which we let out, and local residents. This will inform a debate about what action can be taken to improve air quality in Fitzrovia.

details.name: Abbey Road
details.description:
The Abbey Road node is located on lamp column 001 of Abbey Road, near to the Merton High Street/Abbey Road junction. The node is approximately 3.5m high and 1m from the kerb. 
The Abbey Road node is also referred to as the Sustainable Merton node as they and the Merton Citizen Scientists were awarded the node as part of the Breathe London Community Programme.

details.name: Branch Road
details.description:
The Friends of Limehouse are taking a systematic approach towards improving our natural environment, which includes reducing air pollution. 

Air pollution levels in Limehouse are amongst the highest in London and are the highest in LB Tower Hamlets by 30%.  The levels are recorded by an LBTH sensor (No35) located to the west of the Limehouse Link and Rotherhithe tunnel portals, and to the junction of Branch Road with Commercial Road, where excessive traffic congestion is common. 

The new Breathe London sensor is located in Branch Road on the east side of the pollution source where levels are likely to be higher than at the existing sensor due the prevailing westerly wind.

We have provided proposals to the authorities on how traffic congestion and hence pollution might be reduced at its source; and have obtained proposals by specialist consultants for a Green Infrastructure Masterplan, including air pollution reduction at its source and beyond.  The GI Masterplan would provide many other benefits such as active travel, community cohesion and enhanced biodiversity.

The additional sensor now located on Branch Road will be invaluable in providing further evidence for the approval of the measures necessary to reduce air pollution and to monitor subsequent improvements.

details.name: Elthorne Park & Leighton Roads Residents Association
Mary Immaculate and St. Peter's Church
details.description: Several factors have come together to highlight the importance of understanding the quality of the air we breath in and around Chipping Barnet Foodbank. Firstly, we are a service that supports vulnerable people in our community. Many of our clients have adverse medical conditions and experience poverty. When these factors are combined with poor air quality, we know that this can make for significantly worse health outcomes. Secondly, we are based near one of the larger construction sites in the London Borough of Barnet called The Victoria Quarter. In fact, we used to be based on this site and we now reside a couple of hundred metres up the road. It is estimated that 19% of air pollution in Barnet is caused by construction sites. A third factor is the introduction of the Ultra Low Emission Zone (ULEZ). Barnet has been deeply emersed in the debate about ULEZ and passions run high in the suburb. Considering these factors, we are delighted to have a node which is based just outside the entrance to our hall, and which will accurately capture the life of the foodbank from client footfall to delivery traffic to our small carpark. We plan to use the node as an educational platform for the food bank, the parish, and the local community with a view to monitoring and campaigning for good air quality inside as well as outside

details.name: Connaught Village
details.description: Looking at the impact of air pollution on visitors to Connaught Village. The village has significant through traffic: how much does this reduce the quality of the air that visitors to the shops and cafes breathe?

details.name: Surrey Docks Farm
details.description: The group are excited to be part of the project to deepen their understanding about pollution and the quality of our environment and learn what impact the green space we help care for makes on the data!
